        <div id="detail-vs" class="detail-panel">
            <h3 class="detail-title">Development Environment: Visual Studio 2026 Preview</h3>
            <p class="detail-content">
                This project was engineered using the cutting-edge VS 2026 ecosystem to utilize advanced <strong>Hot Reload</strong> capabilities for rapid prototyping.
                I structured the solution architecture following the <strong>Clean Architecture</strong> principle separating the Data Access Layer (DAL) from the Presentation Layer to enforce strict <strong>Separation of Concerns</strong>.
                Integrated NuGet package management handles dependencies like Entity Framework Core ensuring strict version consistency across local development and production build servers.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div id="detail-ssms" class="detail-panel">
            <h3 class="detail-title">Database Management: SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS)</h3>
            <p class="detail-content">
                SSMS is utilized here for advanced query profiling and <strong>Execution Plan analysis</strong>. I use it to identify table scan bottlenecks and author raw T-SQL migration scripts when EF Core migrations require manual intervention.
                The environment is configured to monitor deadlock graphs and ensure that our stored procedures are optimized for sub-second response times even under concurrent user load. I also manage database schemas through visual diagrams to enforce referential integrity constraints before code generation.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div id="detail-cloud" class="detail-panel">
            <h3 class="detail-title">CI/CD & Cloud Troubleshooting</h3>
            <p class="detail-content">
                Deployment is handled via Azure Pipelines (DevOps) but the real engineering challenge was the database connectivity. I hit a persistent <strong>Error 40 / Named Pipes Provider</strong> failure where the app service refused to handshake with the Azure SQL database despite firewall rules being open. After exhaustive root-cause analysis testing connection strings checking port 1433 outbound rules and verifying Entra ID authentication I confirmed it was a platform-level sync issue on the Azure backend. Instead of waiting on support tickets I pivoted to <strong>ngrok</strong> to bypass the cloud network stack entirely. This allowed me to tunnel the local environment directly to the public web and get the site live immediately proving that the code was solid and the issue was purely infrastructural.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

