    <div id="deep-dive" class="tech-section">
        <h2 class="section-header">Insight Security: Core Technology Stack</h2>
        <p class="text-center mb-5" style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; color: var(--text-body);">
            A detailed breakdown of the architectural decisions powering this platform.
        </p>

        <div class="stack-entry">
            <h3 class="stack-title">SQL Database Architecture</h3>
            <p class="stack-desc">
                The persistence layer is engineered using Microsoft SQL Server adhering to strict relational database design principles to ensure data integrity. The schema is normalized to the <strong>Third Normal Form (3NF)</strong> to minimize redundancy while utilizing strategic non-clustered indexes to accelerate lookups on high-traffic columns. I leverage Stored Procedures and parameterized queries exclusively to abstract business logic from the data layer and provide a hard-stop defense against SQL Injection attacks. The database utilizes T-SQL for complex join operations and transaction management ensuring <strong>ACID compliance</strong> (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) across all data mutations.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="stack-entry">
            <h3 class="stack-title">C#.NET Core Middleware</h3>
            <p class="stack-desc">
                The application core is built on the .NET 8 framework leveraging its cross-platform capabilities and high-performance Kestrel web server. I utilize the built-in <strong>Dependency Injection (DI)</strong> container to manage service lifecycles (Singleton, Scoped, Transient) promoting loose coupling and testability. The architecture implements the Repository Pattern to abstract data access while the business logic relies on asynchronous programming models (<code>async</code>/<code>await</code>) to prevent thread-pool starvation under load. Strong typing and LINQ are used extensively to enforce compile-time safety.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="stack-entry">
            <h3 class="stack-title">ASP.NET Razor Pages (SSR)</h3>
            <p class="stack-desc">
                The presentation layer utilizes ASP.NET Core Razor Pages a page-focused framework that streamlines the MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) pattern for web scenarios. Unlike heavy client-side frameworks Razor Pages delivers <strong>Server-Side Rendering (SSR)</strong> ensuring rapid First Contentful Paint (FCP) and superior SEO optimization. I utilize Tag Helpers to create semantic maintainable HTML that binds seamlessly to the backing <code>PageModel</code> classes. The architecture leverages Partial Views for reusable UI components and employs Anti-Forgery Tokens automatically on all form submissions to secure user interactions against CSRF attacks.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="modal fade" id="minerModal" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
        <div class="modal-dialog modal-lg modal-dialog-centered">
            <div class="modal-content shadow-lg" style="background-color: var(--bg-surface); border: 1px solid var(--brand-primary);">
                <div class="modal-header" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--bg-accent);">
                    <h5 class="modal-title fw-bold" style="color: var(--brand-primary);">
                        <i class="bi bi-tools me-2"></i>MinerControlCenter: Technical Breakdown
                    </h5>
                    <button type="button" class="btn-close btn-close-white" data-bs-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close"></button>
                </div>
                <div class="modal-body p-4">
                    <h6 class="fw-bold mb-3" style="color: var(--brand-primary); font-size: 1.1rem;">Core Engineering Walkthrough</h6>
                    <div style="color: #e2e8f0; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6;">
                        <p>
                            This isn't a standard web app hitting a nice clean REST API. This is a C# WPF desktop application that has to get its hands dirty talking directly to hardware. I bypassed standard HTTP interfaces entirely because they are too slow for real-time monitoring of large fleets. Instead the app manages asynchronous <code>System.Net.Sockets.TcpClient</code> connections opened directly to port 4028 on every miner on the subnet simultaneously.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Once the TCP handshake is fine I have to serialize custom JSON-RPC packets. Literally converting strings like <code>{"command": "stats"}</code> into raw byte arrays and blasting them down the wire. The hardest part is handling the response. ASIC firmware returns massive messy strings of data that are formatted differently depending on if it's an M30s++ an M50 or an Antminer. Standard JSON deserializers choke on it.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To fix that I wrote complex compiled Regex patterns to define capture groups for critical data points. The app parses these raw streams in real-time to extract chip temps PCB temps fan duty cycles and MH/s rates. It then normalizes it all into C# objects that the UI can actually bind to. It also includes an async safety loop that monitors those Regex captures. If a hashboard hits 85°C it automatically fires a stop command packet to save the hardware.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row g-3 mt-4">
                        <div class="col-md-4">
                            <div class="p-3 rounded-3 h-100" style="background: var(--bg-body); border: 1px solid var(--brand-primary);">
